## What Does NOT Require Re-Authorization

Equally important is understanding what the ongoing authorization model specifically does not require re-authorization for:

Routine security patches, including Critical patches applied within SLA, do not require re-authorization. This is expected maintenance, not a material change to the authorization basis.

New POA&M items from continuous monitoring findings do not require re-authorization as long as the findings are Low or Moderate severity, compensating controls are documented, and remediation is on track. The authorization explicitly acknowledged that POA&M items would be added and managed through the authorization period.

Personnel changes in non-AO roles (ISSO, IT Administrator, Health IT Manager) do not require re-authorization if the incoming personnel have appropriate qualifications and a documented handoff ensures continuity. Personnel changes that affect the AO role itself require the new AO to review and affirm the existing authorization — they cannot inherit responsibility for a risk acceptance they have not made.

Minor SSP updates reflecting implementation changes or documentation improvements do not require re-authorization. These are administrative maintenance of the authorization package, not changes to the security posture.

The underlying principle: re-authorization is required when the risk picture has changed materially in a way that the AO's original acceptance no longer covers. Routine operations within the accepted risk envelope — including managing findings through the POA&M process — are part of what the AO authorized, not events that interrupt it.

