## The 45-Day CP-2 Check-In — AO Engagement in Action

The 45-day check-in happening this week is an example of ongoing authorization operating as designed. The authorization condition was set because the CP-2 gap was the most significant operational risk item at authorization. The check-in was specified in the authorization conditions — not as a courtesy, but as a governance mechanism to ensure the AO has visibility at the point where there is still enough time to intervene if things are off track.

The Health IT Manager's briefing to the AO should cover: Milestone completion status (1 and 2 complete, 3 and 4 scheduled with specific dates), the clinical leadership attendance status for the Milestone 3 meeting, any obstacles that have emerged in the drafting process, and the realistic probability of meeting the 12-day deadline.

The AO's engagement at the check-in should not be passive confirmation that the ISSO's report is received. The AO should ask: "What do you need from me to make the Milestone 3 meeting happen on schedule?" The one unresponsive clinical leadership participant represents exactly the kind of obstacle that requires AO-level authority to resolve. The ISSO cannot compel clinical leadership attendance. The Executive Director can.

This is ongoing authorization working at its best — the AO is not a rubber-stamp signature on quarterly reports. They are an active participant in maintaining the security posture they authorized, exercising their organizational authority at the moments when it is needed.

