## Ongoing Authorization vs. Traditional Periodic Authorization — Honest Assessment

The ongoing authorization model is more demanding than the traditional model — it requires genuine ongoing AO engagement, a functioning continuous monitoring program, and the discipline to report accurately including unflattering findings like AT RISK condition status. Organizations that cannot sustain that level of engagement often find the traditional periodic model operationally easier.

The honest tradeoff: the traditional model concentrates the security assessment and AO engagement effort at three-year intervals, which is operationally manageable but produces three-year periods of declining authorization accuracy. The ongoing model distributes that effort continuously, which is operationally more demanding but produces a continuously accurate authorization picture.

For a High-impact healthcare system processing ePHI used in real-time clinical decision support — which is what MyClinic's OpenMRS is — the ongoing model's continuous accuracy is worth the operational investment. A traditional three-year model for a system at this impact level means the AO may be operating on authorization documentation that is 18 months out of date at the midpoint of the authorization period. That is not consistent with the risk management obligations that come with a High-impact system authorization.

The ongoing authorization model is not just more modern — for a system like OpenMRS, it is more appropriate.

