## What I Am Still Thinking About

The three-year authorization expiration and re-authorization cycle — even under the ongoing authorization model — raises a question about organizational learning.

At the end of the three-year authorization period, MyClinic will initiate re-authorization. The re-authorization will include an updated assessment. The updated assessment will evaluate the system as it exists three years into operations — with the benefit of everything the continuous monitoring program has produced, all the findings identified and remediated, all the process improvements made, and all the institutional knowledge accumulated.

That accumulated knowledge is what I want to ensure is captured formally in the re-authorization package — not just the current state of controls, but the story of how the security program matured. What did the first formal assessment find that the internal implementation work had missed? What did the continuous monitoring program surface that neither the implementation work nor the formal assessment had caught? What process design improvements were made based on operational experience?

This organizational learning narrative — captured in the annual continuous monitoring summaries and the monitoring logs over the three-year period — is a genuinely valuable input to the re-authorization process. It tells the next assessor what the organization has learned about its own system, what the persistent risks are, and where the security program has grown. That context makes the re-authorization assessment more efficient and more valuable than a cold-start assessment of a system the assessor has never seen before.

